After posting my last comment, I realized that if the requirement is to have a solution that does not require changing the page's HTML, my solution is only viable if:
1) jQuery is already being loaded. This isn't fatal, but you'd have to manipulate the DOM without it.
2) The page already loads a script file into which you can put the code to manipulate the DOM. This is the critical piece. If it doesn't already load any JS under your control, then there's no way to inject the spaces, jQuery or no.

Indeed, the jquery solution could run into browser performance issues on slower systems, of which many old Sun Ray servers could be classified as. So the correct solution depends on which is more important: performance, correct copy/paste as text, and leaving the original HTML unaltered. As is the usual mantra: "pick two"...
While the bug itself is not directly related to this issue, I found the following on firefox: https://bugzilla.mozilla.org/show_bug_cgi?id=116083 . The following comment explains why CSS styling (content property) did nothing:
> Currently, we copy what's in the dom, not what CSS is making us show on the screen. We spent many days early on talking about how we might be able to copy taking CSS into account, but never came up with a design everyone could agree with (let along find time to implement it in a way that offered reasonable performance).
As an interesting side note, that bug is now over 10 years old...
